<dl id="n13102b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n13" href="#n13102b">N13 (VI.D.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n13all.htm#n13102b"> 102(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> post <font face="wake">+</font>ian</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It is this easy analysis of our early literature into its ante-Christian and its <mark>post-Christian</mark> elements which makes it so valuable. For when all spurious accretions have been stripped off, we find in our most ancient tales a genuine picture of Pagan life in Europe, for which we look in vain elsewhere. <small> Douglas Hyde, <a name="SEGL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SEGL"><cite title="source">The Story of Early Gaelic Literature</cite></a> (1920) 41</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05041b" href="c5all.htm#c05041b">VI.C.05:041(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
